<paragraph blockId="64.[151,1437,833,2009]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,466,905,930]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
A strongly shining species, with dorsal punctation very fine and sparse; the punctures on the pronotal disc are smaller than the largest punctures on the frons, an unusual condition. The elytra are unusual in that the punctures become slightly coarser posteriorly, and many of the punctures on the disc are random or only subserial. Similar in dorsal habitus to 
<taxonomicName authority="Perkins" authorityName="Perkins" box="[588,783,1013,1037]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jivaro">
<emphasis box="[588,690,1014,1037]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">H. jivaro</emphasis>
Perkins
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[800,910,1013,1037]" captionStart="FIGURE 102" captionStartId="142.[151,250,1650,1673]" captionTargetBox="[256,1333,213,1613]" captionTargetId="figure@142.[237,1350,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId="142" captionText="FIGURE 102. Hydraena jivaro, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1050174/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
Figs. 
<number box="[866,910,1013,1037]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" value="102138.0">102</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[924,969,1013,1037]" captionStart="FIGURE 138" captionStartId="168.[151,250,1650,1673]" captionTargetBox="[252,1334,193,1626]" captionTargetId="figure@168.[252,1334,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId="168" captionText="FIGURE 138. Hydraena flagella, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1050212/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">138</figureCitation>
); differentiated therefrom by the slightly finer pronotal punctation, the greater degree of randomness of the basal elytral punctures, the narrower P 
<number box="[1328,1343,1049,1073]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" value="2.0">2</number>
, and the differently shaped plaques (arcuate and larger in 
<taxonomicName box="[695,814,1085,1109]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flagella">
<emphasis box="[695,814,1085,1109]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">H. flagella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The aedeagi of the two species are similar in the presence of a long gonopore-bearing flagellum, the presence of long setae on the dorsal surface, and general shape, but markedly differ in many details (
<figureCitation box="[519,626,1157,1181]" captionStart="FIGURES 105 – 107" captionStartId="145.[151,264,1650,1673]" captionText="FIGURES 105 – 107. Aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
Figs. 
<number box="[582,626,1157,1181]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" value="105140.0">105</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[638,684,1157,1181]" captionStart="FIGURES 140 – 141" captionStartId="170.[151,264,1650,1673]" captionText="FIGURES 140 – 141. Aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="64" pageNumber="65">140</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
