</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[151,1436,151,536]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,476,500]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Notes.</emphasis>
The aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName box="[468,587,476,500]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flagella">
<emphasis box="[468,587,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">H. flagella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[602,697,476,500]" captionStart="FIGURES 140 – 141" captionStartId="170.[151,264,1650,1673]" captionText="FIGURES 140 – 141. Aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
Fig. 
<number box="[654,697,476,500]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" value="140.0">140</number>
</figureCitation>
) has three long setae on the dorsal surface, perhaps indicating that this species is related to those in the 
<taxonomicName box="[560,631,513,536]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="65" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jivaro">
<emphasis box="[560,631,513,536]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Jivaro</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Complex.
</paragraph>
